---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import marsLocations from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'jezero-crater');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Jezero Crater location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Jezero Crater - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-gray-800 to-gray-900 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Perseverance rover's 360-degree mosaic from "Airey Hill"
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL-Caltech/ASU/MSSS</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Jezero Crater is one of the most scientifically significant locations
          on Mars, serving as the landing site for NASA's Perseverance rover
          mission. This ancient impact crater, formed nearly 4 billion years
          ago, once hosted a large lake fed by an ancient river delta system.
          The crater preserves a remarkable geological record spanning over 3.5
          billion years of Martian history.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The name "Jezero" comes from the Bosnian word for "lake," which is
          fitting given the crater's history as a paleolake. The delta formation
          within Jezero is exceptionally well-preserved, making it an ideal
          location to search for signs of ancient microbial life and to
          understand Mars' past habitability.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Since February 2021, the Perseverance rover has been systematically
          exploring Jezero, collecting rock samples for eventual return to Earth
          and making groundbreaking discoveries about Mars' geological and
          hydrological history.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Diameter:</span>
            <span class="text-white">49 km (30 miles)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Age:</span>
            <span class="text-white">~3.9 billion years</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Current Mission:</span>
            <span class="text-white">Perseverance Rover</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Landing Date:</span>
            <span class="text-white">February 18, 2021</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Samples Collected:</span>
            <span class="text-white">24+ rock/soil samples</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Geological History -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Geological History
    </h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
          Formation and Early History
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Jezero Crater formed almost 4 billion years ago from an asteroid
          impact. The crater floor is made of igneous rock formed from magma
          underground or volcanic activity at the surface. After the crater's
          formation, it remained relatively dry for hundreds of millions of
          years.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The first evidence of water appeared when rivers began flowing into
          the crater, depositing sandstone and mudstone layers. This marked the
          beginning of Jezero's transformation into a lake basin.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">Lake Period</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Over time, Jezero hosted a lake that grew as wide as 22 miles (35
          kilometers) in diameter and as deep as 100 feet (30 meters). Salt-rich
          mudstones indicate periods when the shallow lake experienced
          evaporation.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Fast-flowing water later carried boulders from outside Jezero,
          distributing them atop the delta and throughout the crater, suggesting
          dramatic flooding events in the lake's later history.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Current Mission -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Perseverance Mission Discoveries
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-8">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
          Sample Collection Achievements
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          As of late 2023, Perseverance has collected over 24 samples from
          Jezero Crater. Two samples stand out for their astrobiological
          significance:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-300 space-y-2">
          <li>
            <strong>"Lefroy Bay":</strong> Contains fine-grained silica, a material
            known to preserve ancient fossils on Earth
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>"Otis Peak":</strong> Rich in phosphate, often associated with
            life as we know it, and carbonate minerals
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div class="bg-gray-800/30 rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-700">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-3">
            Water History Evidence
          </h3>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Perseverance has found clear evidence of Jezero's watery past,
            including delta deposits, sedimentary layers, and mineral formations
            that only occur in the presence of liquid water. These discoveries
            provide a timeline of environmental changes over billions of years.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gray-800/30 rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-700">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-3">
            Organic Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            The combination of carbonates, phosphates, and fine-grained silica
            creates ideal conditions for preserving signs of ancient life. These
            minerals point to a watery, habitable environment with excellent
            preservation potential.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Potential -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming and Settlement Potential
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          With a terraforming rating of 9/10, Jezero Crater represents one of
          Mars' most promising locations for future human settlement. Its rich
          geological diversity, evidence of past habitability, and ongoing
          scientific mission make it an invaluable site for understanding Mars'
          potential for life.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
          Key Advantages
        </h3>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Resource Availability</h4>
            <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-1">
              <li>• Evidence of subsurface water/ice</li>
              <li>• Clay-rich sediments for construction</li>
              <li>• Diverse mineral resources</li>
              <li>• Relatively flat delta region</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Scientific Value</h4>
            <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-1">
              <li>• Proven landing site accessibility</li>
              <li>• Rich geological record</li>
              <li>• Potential biosignature preservation</li>
              <li>• Ongoing mission infrastructure</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-mars-900/30 rounded-lg p-6 border border-mars-600">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
          Settlement Challenges
        </h3>
        <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-2">
          <li>• Dust accumulation during storms</li>
          <li>• High radiation exposure</li>
          <li>• Extreme temperature fluctuations</li>
          <li>• Limited current water access</li>
          <li>• Thin atmosphere challenges</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Exploration -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Exploration
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-r from-mars-900/40 to-gray-800/40 rounded-lg p-8 border border-mars-600"
    >
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-mars-orange mb-4">
        Mars Sample Return Mission
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The samples collected by Perseverance at Jezero Crater are scheduled to
        be retrieved and returned to Earth as part of the Mars Sample Return
        mission, planned for the early 2030s. This will be the first time
        Martian materials are brought to Earth for detailed laboratory analysis.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Laboratory analysis of these samples will provide unprecedented insights
        into Mars' past habitability and potentially answer the fundamental
        question of whether life ever existed on Mars.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Planned Investigations</h4>
          <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>• Detailed age dating of rock samples</li>
            <li>• Biosignature detection and analysis</li>
            <li>• Mineral composition studies</li>
            <li>• Organic compound identification</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Scientific Impact</h4>
          <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>• Understanding Mars' climate evolution</li>
            <li>• Assessing past habitability conditions</li>
            <li>• Informing future human missions</li>
            <li>• Advancing astrobiology research</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources -->
  <section>
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <a
          href="https://science.nasa.gov/mission/mars-2020-perseverance/science/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-4 bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg border border-gray-700 hover:border-mars-500 transition-colors group"
        >
          <h3
            class="font-semibold text-white group-hover:text-mars-orange transition-colors mb-2"
          >
            NASA Perseverance Science
          </h3>
          <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm">
            Official NASA mission science overview and latest discoveries
          </p>
        </a>

        <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jezero_%28crater%29"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-4 bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg border border-gray-700 hover:border-mars-500 transition-colors group"
        >
          <h3
            class="font-semibold text-white group-hover:text-mars-orange transition-colors mb-2"
          >
            Jezero Crater - Wikipedia
          </h3>
          <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm">
            Comprehensive overview of crater geology and exploration history
          </p>
        </a>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <a
          href="https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/nasas-perseverance-rover-deciphers-ancient-history-of-martian-lake/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-4 bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg border border-gray-700 hover:border-mars-500 transition-colors group"
        >
          <h3
            class="font-semibold text-white group-hover:text-mars-orange transition-colors mb-2"
          >
            Ancient Lake History
          </h3>
          <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm">
            Latest research on Jezero's ancient lake and delta system
          </p>
        </a>

        <a
          href="https://mars.nasa.gov/mars2020/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="block p-4 bg-gray-800/50 rounded-lg border border-gray-700 hover:border-mars-500 transition-colors group"
        >
          <h3
            class="font-semibold text-white group-hover:text-mars-orange transition-colors mb-2"
          >
            Mars 2020 Mission
          </h3>
          <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm">
            Real-time mission updates and rover status
          </p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>

